 false, "mention": "testosterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9687590003013611, "span": {"begin": 328, "end": 340}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:16469"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "estradiol", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9991403818130493, "span": {"begin": 389, "end": 398}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "ovarian granulosa cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.7493749260902405, "span": {"begin": 416, "end": 439}}], "text": "Theca cell-derived androgens (e.g., testosterone, androstenedione) are precursors for estrogen (e.g., 17&beta;-estradiol, estrone) synthesis. Androgens secreted from the theca cells are aromatized to estrogens in the ovarian granulosa cells (Norris 2007; Senthilkumaran et al. 2004).&nbsp;Consequently, reductions in theca cell testosterone synthesis can be expected to reduce the rate of estradiol synthesis by the ovarian granulosa cells (Payne and Hales 2004; Miller 1988; Nagahama et al. 1993).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:34:09 +0000 2026"}